Arrays: Data structures that can store myltiple values in a single variable
Example Array:
const cars = ["Toyota", "Hyundai", "Kia"];

- Array declarations can span multiple lines
- You can create an array and then provide elements:
  const cars = [];
  cars[0] = "Toyota";
  cars[1] = "Hyundai";
  cars[2] = "Kia";

- Converting an Array to a string
- toString() method converts an array to a string of comma separated array values
  const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple"];
  document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = fruits.toString();

- Access the whole array:
const cars = ["Toyota", "Hyundai", "Kia"];
document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = cars;

- Arrays use numbers to aacess its elements starting with 0 being the first element
const pers = ["John", "Kyle", "Alex"];
console.log(pers[0]);
OUTPUT: John

- Array Properties and Methods
  - sort(): sorts the array
  - length(): returns the number of elements in the array
  - You can acces the last Array element by attaching - 1 to the end
  of .length
  - Array at(): Returns an indexed element from an array
  - Array join(): Joins all array elements into a string but you can specify the separator
  - Array pop(): Removes the last element from an array
  - Array push(): Returns the new array length
  - Array shift(): Removes the first array element and shifts all other elemenets to lower
  index
  - Array unshift(): Adds a new element to an array (at the beginning), and unshifts older
  older elements
  - Array concat(): Creates a new array by merging existing arrays
  - Array copyWithin(): Copies array elements to another position in an array
  - 

- Looping Array Elements:

const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
let fLen = fruits.length;

let text = "<ul>";
for (let i = 0; i < fLen; i++) {
  text += "<li>" + fruits[i] "</li>";
}
text += "</ul>";

You can also use the Array.forEach() function:

const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];

let text = "<ul>";
fruits.forEach(myFunction);
text += "</ul>";

function myFunction(value) {
  text += "<li>" + value + "</li>";
} 


- Adding Array Elements
  - push() method
const fruits = ["banana", "orange", "apple"];
fruits.push("Lemon"); // Adds a new elements to fruits
  
